                      "id": "post-s5-math-1",
                      "title": "Understanding limits and continuity",
                      "content": "I'm struggling with the concept of limits in calculus. Can someone explain when a function is continuous?",
                      "authorId": "student-3",
                      "authorName": "Sarah Namuli",
                      "authorRole": "student",
                      "createdAt": "2025-06-21T13:45:00Z",
                      "updatedAt": "2025-06-21T13:45:00Z",
                      "replies": [
                        {
                          "id": "reply-s5-math-1-1",
                          "content": "A function is continuous at a point if the limit exists and equals the function value at that point. Think of it as being able to draw the graph without lifting your pen.",
                          "authorId": "teacher-math-adv",
                          "authorName": "Prof. James Mukasa",
                          "authorRole": "teacher",
                          "createdAt": "2025-06-21T14:20:00Z",
                          "likes": 22,
                          "isTeacherApproved": true
                        }
                      ],
                      "tags": ["mathematics", "calculus", "limits", "continuity", "senior-5"],
                      "views": 156,
                      "likes": 34,
                      "isPinned": false,
                      "isSolved": true
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "id": "cat-senior-5-physics",
                  "name": "Physics",
                  "level": "subject",
                  "posts": [
                    {
                      "id": "post-s5-phy-1",
                      "title": "Circular motion and centripetal force",
                      "content": "How do I calculate centripetal force for uniform circular motion? The formula seems confusing.",
                      "authorId": "student-3",
                      "authorName": "Sarah Namuli",
                      "authorRole": "student",
                      "createdAt": "2025-06-20T11:30:00Z",
                      "updatedAt": "2025-06-20T11:30:00Z",
                      "replies": [
                        {
                          "id": "reply-s5-phy-1-1",
                          "content": "The centripetal force formula is F = mv²/r, where m is mass, v is velocity, and r is radius. Remember, this force always points toward the center of the circle.",
                          "authorId": "teacher-phy-adv",
                          "authorName": "Dr. Mary Nakirya",
                          "authorRole": "teacher",
                          "createdAt": "2025-06-20T12:00:00Z",
                          "likes": 18,
                          "isTeacherApproved": true
                        }
                      ],
                      "tags": ["physics", "circular-motion", "centripetal-force", "senior-5"],
                      "views": 92,
                      "likes": 27,
                      "isPinned": false,
                      "isSolved": true
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
